<section xml:id="sec-Banzhaf-Power-Index">
    <title>Banzhaf Power Index</title>
    <p>
        power index!Banzhaf
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <definition xml:id="def-coalition">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                      A coalition is? 
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>
                
            <solution>
                <p>
                  any set of players that might join forces and vote the same way.
                In principle, we can have a coalition with as few as <em>one</em> player and as many as <em>all</em> players.
                The coalition consisting of all the players is called the <alert>grand coalition</alert>.
                Since coalitions are just sets of players, the most convenient way to describe coalitions mathematically is to use the <em>set</em> notation.  
                </p>
            </solution>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Consider a weighted voting system with three voters <m>P_{1}</m>, <m>P_{2}</m>, and <m>P_{3}</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            List all the coalitions.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            How many are there?
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <m>\begin{array}{c}\{P_1\}, \{P_2\}, \{P_3\}\\
                            \{P_1, P_2\}, \{P_1, P_3\}, \{P_2, P_3\}\\ \{P_1, P_2, P_3\}\end{array}</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Consider a weighted voting system with four voters <m>P_{1}</m>, <m>P_{2}</m>, <m>P_{3}</m>, and <m>P_{4}</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            List all the coalitions.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            How many are there?
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <m>\begin{array}{c}\{P_1\}, \{P_2\}, \{P_3\}, \{P_4\}\\ \{P_1, P_2\}, \{P_1, P_3\}, \{P_1, P_4\}, \{P_2, P_3\}, \{P_2, P_4\}, \{P_3, P_4\}\\ \{P_1, P_2, P_3\}, \{P_1, P_3, P_4\}, \{P_1, P_2, P_4\}, \{P_2, P_3, P_4\}\\ \{P_1, P_2, P_3, P_4\}\end{array}</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If a weighted voting system has <m>n</m> voters <m>P_{1}</m>, <m>P_{2}</m>, …, <m>P_{n}</m>,
                        </p>

                        <task>
